[[File:Exterior of the animatronic depiction of waterboarding from Coney Island.jpg|thumb|Exterior of the animatronic depiction of waterboarding from [[Coney Island]].]]
In the summer of 2008 [[conceptual art]]ist [[Steve Powers (artist)|Steve Powers]] conceived a work that came to be known as the '''Coney Island waterboarding thrill ride''' on [[Coney Island]].<ref name=NYMag2008-06-27> {{cite news |url = http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2008/06/any_lawyers_want_to_get_waterb.html |title = Steve Powers Wants to See You Get Waterboarded |date = 2008-06-27 |author = |publisher = [[New York Magazine]] |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnymag.com%2Fdaily%2Fintel%2F2008%2F06%2Fany_lawyers_want_to_get_waterb.html&date=2009-04-19 |archivedate = 2009-04-19 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost2008-08-17> {{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/16/AR2008081602071.html |title = In N.Y., Waterboarding as Dark Art |work = The Washington Post |date = 2008-08-17 |accessdate = 2011-11-11 |quote = He first wanted real people to undergo waterboarding for the public, but he realized that might be tricky and limited it to the one-time private experiment. For the public display, with robotic stand-ins, Powers concerned himself with details such as finding music mentioned on blogs as having been played to prisoners at Abu Ghraib and Guantanamo. |page = |author = Robin Shulman |deadurl = bot: unknown |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/637bFEWBk?url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/16/AR2008081602071.html |archivedate = 2011-11-11 |df = }}
[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fwp-dyn%2Fcontent%2Farticle%2F2008%2F08%2F16%2FAR2008081602071_2.html&date=2011-11-11 mirror] </ref><ref name=NytimeArts2008> {{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/30/arts/30arts-WATERBOARDIN_BRF.html |title=Waterboarding as Art |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=2008-07-30 |accessdate=2011-11-11 |quote=The journalist Christopher Hitchens underwent waterboarding for a recent Vanity Fair article. Now an artist is using that interrogation technique — which makes people feel as if they were drowning — to raise awareness of the issue of torture. |page= |author=Julie Bloom |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/637cl58eB?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/30/arts/30arts-WATERBOARDIN_BRF.html |archivedate=2011-11-11 |df= }}
</ref>
As originally conceived, Powers saw the public watching volunteers undergoing actual [[waterboarding]].<ref name=NYMag2008-06-27/> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that on August 17, 2008 Powers brought in [[Mike Ritz]], a former US official experienced in administering waterboarding, for a one time demonstration of waterboarding on volunteers.<ref name=WashingtonPost2008-08-17/> This demonstration was not open to the general public, but rather for an invited audience. Powers himself was one of the volunteers.
As built, the [[Amusement ride|thrill ride]] was a diorama, where viewers would mount stairs to a window where they would see a tableau of two models, one a captive, one a masked interrogator. The captive was wearing an [[Guantanamo captives' uniform|orange uniform]] "[[non-compliant]]" captives wear in the [[United States]]' [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s, in [[Cuba]], and was spread-eagled on a tilted table.
When the piece was installed, in July 2008, viewers inserted a dollar the interrogator figure would pour water onto a rag over the captive figures' nose and throat, upon which the captive figure would start convulsing.
The piece was installed in a row of ordinary Coney Island freak shows and [[concession stand|concessions]]. When installed the thrill ride triggered coverage and commentary around the world.<ref> {{cite news |url = http://www.switched.com/2008/08/07/coney-islands-robotic-waterboard-thrill-ride-evokes-guantanam/ |title = Coney Island's Robotic 'Waterboard Thrill Ride' Evokes Guantanamo |date = 2008-08-07 |author = Will Safer |publisher = [[Huffington Post]] |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fgizmodo.com%2F5034224%2Frobots-act-out-guantanamo-waterboarding-torture-terrorists-win&date=2009-04-17 |archivedate = 2009-04-17 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref><ref> {{cite news |url = http://gothamist.com/2008/08/06/waterboard_thrill_ride_splashes_dow.php |title = Waterboarding an attraction at amusement park |date = 2008-08-07 |author = Ritsuke Ando |publisher = [[Reuters]] |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.switched.com%2F2008%2F08%2F07%2Fconey-islands-robotic-waterboard-thrill-ride-evokes-guantanam%2F&date=2009-04-17 |archivedate = 2009-04-17 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref>
The installation's last viewing was on September 14, 2008.<ref name=Brooklynbased2008September> {{cite news |url = http://brooklynbased.net/everything/patriot-art/ |title = The Waterboard Thrill Ride |quote = Brooklyn artist Steve Powers’ installation has been up since July beside less menacing Coney Island sideshows: Pay $1, and see an animatronic torturer in action. It should be on view 2-6 on Friday and 2-8, Saturday, Sept. 14, when it closes. |date = September 2008 |author = |publisher = [[Brooklynbased]] |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fbrooklynbased.net%2Feverything%2Fpatriot-art%2F&date=2009-04-17 |archivedate = 2009-04-17 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref>
Powers told ''The New York Times'' his purpose in preparing the display was educational: :{| class="wikitable" border="1" | *"What's more obscene, the official position that waterboarding is not torture, or our official position that it's a thrill ride?"<ref name=NYTimes20080807/> *"Robot waterboarding became a way of exploring the issue without doing any harm. It's putting a unique experience on the table. And it doesn't take a great leap of the imagination to look in there and say: 'That's really what's going on? That's crazy.'"<ref name=NYTimes20080807> {{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/06/arts/design/06wate.html?_r=1 |title=Coney Island Sideshow Has Guantánamo Theme |work=The New York Times |first=Ariel |last=Kaminer |date=7 August 2008 |accessdate=20 April 2009 }} </ref> |}
